{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638126"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:49:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:49:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17691"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17691"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72087"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10405"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57557"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10450"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24316"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24365"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72087"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe basilar membrane within the cochlea plays a crucial role in sound frequency discrimination. Its physical properties vary along its length from base to apex.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the relationship between sound frequency and basilar membrane displacement?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Low frequencies cause maximum displacement at the base","High frequencies cause maximum displacement at the apex","High frequencies cause maximum displacement at the base","All frequencies cause equal displacement along the membrane","Frequency has no effect on membrane displacement location"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe basilar membrane exhibits tonotopic organisation, where \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh frequencies cause maximum displacement at the base\u003C/strong\u003E of the cochlea. This occurs because the membrane is narrow and stiff at the base, making it responsive to high frequencies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow frequencies cause maximum displacement at the base\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as low frequencies travel further along the membrane and cause maximum displacement at the apex where the membrane is more flexible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh frequencies cause maximum displacement at the apex\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the apex, being wider and more flexible, responds to low frequencies rather than high frequencies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll frequencies cause equal displacement along the membrane\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as different regions of the membrane respond preferentially to specific frequencies based on their physical properties.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrequency has no effect on membrane displacement location\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as there is a clear relationship between frequency and location of maximum displacement along the membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis arrangement allows for frequency discrimination, as different frequencies activate different populations of hair cells along the basilar membrane. The gradual change in membrane properties from base to apex creates a frequency map within the cochlea.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The basilar membrane becomes wider and more flexible from base to apex of the cochlea.","High frequency sounds cause maximum displacement of the basilar membrane near the base.","Low frequency sounds cause maximum displacement of the basilar membrane near the apex."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57557"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17691"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57557"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:23:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:50:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10405"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72087"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synony